'''''Home Brew''''' is the first [[studio album]] by New Zealand hip hop group [[Home Brew (band)|Home Brew]]. It was released by Young, Gifted & Broke on 1 May 2012. The album draws mainly from the genre of [[New Zealand hip hop]], but is also [[jazz]]-influenced. ''Home Brew'' was promoted by a 48-hour-long release party and a six-show tour of New Zealand cities. The album was lauded by critics, and won the [[New Zealand Music Award for Best Urban/Hip Hop Album]]. It debuted atop the [[New Zealand Albums Chart]].

==Content==
''Home Brew'' is a [[New Zealand hip hop]] album with heavy [[jazz]] influences. It features [[keyboard instrument]]s, [[horn (instrument)|horn]]s, [[saxophone]]s, [[guitar]]s and [[bass (instrument)|bass]]. It is divided into two discs: ''Light'' and ''Dark''. ''Light'' embraces [[welfare fraud]] ("Benefit"), [[alcoholism]] ("Alcoholic") and using [[datura]] as a recreational drug ("Datura/White Flowers"). "Basketball Court" and "Radio" are about nostalgia and memories. ''Dark'' includes "State of Mind", on which band member Tom Scott reflects on his father's time in prison, and "The Truth is Ugly", where he discusses his shortcomings in past romantic relationships. "Listen to Us" criticises the government.<ref name="Appleby"/><ref name="Jenkin"/> Thirty-three songs were recorded for the album; twenty-one made the final cut.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nzmusician.co.nz/index.php/pi_pageid/8/pi_articleid/2647/pi_page/3 |title=Home Brew <U+2013> Setting The Bar |page=3 |work=NZ Musician |first=Gareth |last=Shute |accessdate=10 November 2013 |date=December 2011 <U+2013> January 2012 |volume=16 |issue=7}}</ref>

==Release and promotion==
''Home Brew'' was released in New Zealand and Australia by the [[independent record label]] Young, Gifted & Broke on 1 May 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/home-brew/id518606319 |title=Home Brew |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] ([[Apple Inc.]])|accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/home-brew/id518606319 |title=Home Brew |publisher=iTunes Store (Apple Inc.)|accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> A 48-hour-long launch party titled Home Brew Speakeasy was held from 5 May to 7 May at Shooters Saloon in [[Kingsland, Auckland]]; tickets included a copy of the album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.undertheradar.co.nz/utr/tour/id/2065/title/Home-Brew-Speakeasy---48-Hour-Album-Release-Party.utr |title=Home Brew Speakeasy <U+2013> 48-Hour Album Release Party |publisher=Undertheradar |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1204/S00173/home-brew-release-debut-album.htm |title=Home Brew Release Debut Album |date=11 April 2012 |publisher=[[Home Brew (band)|Home Brew]] |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, Home Brew toured New Zealand on the Home Brew Speakeasy Tour. They performed one show each in [[Auckland]], [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], [[Wellington]], [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]], [[Dunedin]] and [[Christchurch]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1206/S00191/the-home-brew-speakeasy-tour-hits-the-road-in-july.htm |title=The Home Brew Speakeasy Tour Hits The Road in July |publisher=Young, Gifted & Broke |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> Prior to the album's release, [[music video]]s were released for the tracks "Listen to Us" and "Yellow Snot Funk".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzmusician.co.nz/index.php/ps_pagename/article/pi_articleid/2586 |title=Music Video <U+2013> Home Brew <U+2013> Listen To Us |work=NZ Musician |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzmusician.co.nz/index.php/ps_pagename/article/pi_articleid/2688 |title=Music Video <U+2013> Home Brew <U+2013> Yellow Snot Funk |work=NZ Musician |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>

==Reception==
Writing for ''[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]'', Luke Appleby praised the album's beats, instrumentation and lyrical honesty, and gave it five out of five stars.<ref name="Appleby">{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/culture/6934755/Home-Brews-latest-all-about-honesty |title=Home Brew's latest all about honesty |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |publisher=[[Fairfax New Zealand]] |date=17 May 2012 |first=Luke |last=Appleby |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6L1NdUqbG |archivedate=10 November 2013}}</ref> Lydia Jenkin of ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' rated ''Home Brew'' four and a half stars out of five.<ref name="Jenkin">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/music/news/article.cfm?c_id=264&objectid=10804378 |title=Album review: Home Brew <U+2013> Home Brew |first=Lydia |last=Jenkin |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |publisher=[[APN News & Media]] |date=10 May 2012 |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> John Hayden from the ''[[Otago Daily Times]]'' picked ''Home Brew'' as one of the top albums of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/entertainment/music/240208/albums-2012 |title=Albums of 2012 |work=[[Otago Daily Times]] |publisher=[[Allied Press]] |date=22 December 2012 |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> At the [[2012 New Zealand Music Awards]], ''Home Brew'' was nominated in the categories of [[New Zealand Music Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], Best Group, Breakthrough Artist of the Year and [[New Zealand Music Award for Best Urban/Hip Hop Album|Best Urban/Hip Hop Album]]; it won the Urban/Hip Hop Award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzmusicawards.co.nz/2012/11/01/4925/ |title=VNZMA Winners 2012 |publisher=[[New Zealand Music Awards]] |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>

''Home Brew'' did not receive much promotion from [[airplay]] or television screening due to the [[profanities]] contained within the lyrics. However, the album debuted at number one on the [[New Zealand Albums Chart]]<U+2014>the first New Zealand hip hop album to do so since [[Scribe (rapper)|Scribe]]'s ''[[The Crusader (album)|The Crusader]]'' (2003)<U+2014><ref name="Jenkin"/> due to high [[music download|digital]] pre-ordering.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.ripitup.co.nz/music/home-brew-s-album-debut-s-at-1-on-nz-top-40/ |title=Home Brew's Album Debut's at #1 on NZ Top 40 |date=8 May 2012 |work=[[Rip It Up (magazine)|Rip It Up]] |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> The album remained on the albums chart for fifteen weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://charts.org.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Home+Brew&titel=Home+Brew&cat=a |title=Home Brew <U+2013> Home Brew |publisher=Charts.org.nz |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>

